# pyenv
#   For a library or package, you might want to ignore these files since the Python version is usually managed by the user.
#   For an application, you might want to keep these files to ensure all developers use the same Python version.
# .python-version

# pipenv
#   According to pypa/pipenv#598, it is recommended to include Pipfile.lock in version control.
#   However, in case of collaboration, if you are not using Pipenv, you can ignore it.
# Pipfile.lock

# poetry
#   Similar to Pipfile.lock, it is generally recommended to include poetry.lock in version control.
#   https://python-poetry.org/docs/basic-usage/#commit-your-poetrylock-file-to-version-control
# poetry.lock

# pdm
#   Similar to Pipfile.lock, it is generally recommended to include pdm.lock in version control.
#   https://pdm.fming.dev/latest/usage/project/#commit-the-lockfile
# pdm.lock

